  "chunk_index": 32,
  "summary": "Richard confesses to his wife, Theodora, that he is a thief. To avoid disgrace and imprisonment, he reveals that Vincent Easton possesses incriminating documents regarding his illegal dealings. Richard claims he has covered his tracks but fears Easton might inadvertently destroy him if the connection to the data is realized. He pressures Theodora to visit Easton immediately to retrieve the files, suggesting Easton will not refuse her because of his feelings for her. When she resists, Richard pulls a revolver from a drawer and threatens to commit suicide, forcing Theodora to agree to help him.\n\nTheodora travels to Easton’s residence wearing a white mink stole and informs him she is there on behalf of her husband. Easton reveals he has been investigating the fraudulent operations of Hobson, Jekyll, and Lucas, and expresses surprise that Richard is at the top of such a scheme. Despite this, Easton agrees to provide the files. Theodora takes the package and burns the documents in the fireplace.\n\nWhile traveling by taxi from Hampstead toward Chelsea, Theodora experiences internal conflict and doubts herself after seeing Easton, but she ultimately decides to remain loyal to Richard, rationalizing that his crimes are against society rather than her. Upon returning home, a trembling Richard asks if the mission was successful. Theodora confirms she burned the documents herself. Exhausted and pale, she collapses into an armchair, wishing for eternal sleep, while Richard watches her with a mixture of guilt and embarrassment.",
